\begin{definition}
A general linear method is \textit{L-stable} if it is A-stable and
\[
\rho(M(\infty)) = 0.
\]
\end{definition}

context_latex:
\paragraph{Context}
The discussion concerns stability properties of general linear methods for ODEs. A-stability is defined as power-boundedness of \(M(z)\) for all \(z\) in the left half-plane. L-stability is a stronger property that additionally requires the spectral radius to vanish at infinity.

Variables:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \(M(z)\): the stability matrix of the general linear method, a function of the complex parameter \(z\)
    \item \(\rho(M(\infty))\): the spectral radius of \(M(z)\) as \(z \to \infty\)
\end{itemize}
